__data__.text: Louvre Museum - The Louvre Museum is one of the world's largest and most famous museums, housing many works of art, including the Mona Lisa and the Venus de Milo.
Eiffel Tower - The Eiffel Tower is one of the most iconic landmarks in Paris, offering visitors breathtaking views of the city from its observation decks.
Notre-Dame Cathedral - Notre-Dame Cathedral is a masterpiece of French Gothic architecture and one of Paris's most visited attractions, known for its stunning rose windows and sculptures.
Sacré-Cœur Basilica - Located at the summit of Montmartre, the Sacré-Cœur Basilica offers panoramic views of Paris and is known for its white domes and vibrant mosaics.
Musée d'Orsay - The Musée d'Orsay is renowned for its extensive collection of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist masterpieces by artists such as Monet, Van Gogh, and Degas.
Luxembourg Gardens - The Luxembourg Gardens are a peaceful retreat in the heart of Paris, featuring beautifully landscaped gardens, fountains, and statues.
Sainte-Chapelle - Sainte-Chapelle is a Gothic chapel known for its magnificent stained glass windows depicting biblical scenes.
Centre Pompidou - The Centre Pompidou is a cultural hub housing the National Museum of Modern Art, and is known for its innovative architecture.
Palace of Versailles - Located just outside Paris, the Palace of Versailles is a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its opulent architecture, beautiful gardens, and the Hall of Mirrors.
Seine River Cruises - Seine River Cruises offer a unique way to see many of Paris's most famous landmarks from the water.
Le Marais - Le Marais is a historic district in Paris known for its vibrant nightlife, including pubs and restaurants, as well as its architecture and museums.
Montmartre - Montmartre is a bohemian district known for its artists, cafes, and the bustling Place du Tertre.
Champs-Élysées - The Champs-Élysées is one of the most famous avenues in the world, lined with shops, theaters, and cafes, and ending at the Arc de Triomphe.
Père Lachaise Cemetery - Père Lachaise Cemetery is the largest cemetery in Paris, known for its beautiful tombs and as the final resting place of many famous individuals.
Catacombs of Paris - The Catacombs of Paris offer a unique underground tour of the city's history, with tunnels lined with the bones of millions of Parisians.
Moulin Rouge - The Moulin Rouge is a world-famous cabaret known for its spectacular dance shows and the birthplace of the can-can dance.
Le Procope - Le Procope is Paris's oldest cafe, founded in 1686, and has been a meeting place for intellectuals and artists throughout history.
Boulevard Saint-Germain - Boulevard Saint-Germain is known for its bookshops, cafes, and boutiques, making it a popular spot for both locals and tourists.
Place de la Concorde - Place de la Concorde is one of Paris's major public squares, known for its obelisk, fountains, and historical significance.
Tuileries Garden - The Tuileries Garden is located between the Louvre Museum and Place de la Concorde, offering a serene escape with its formal gardens and sculptures.

Eiffel Tower - The Eiffel Tower is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris, France. It is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel, whose company designed and built the tower. Visitors can ascend by stairs or lift to the first and second levels, or take a lift to the top level for stunning views of Paris. The tower has restaurants on the first and second levels, a champagne bar on the top level, and a private apartment built for Gustave Eiffel's use. It's a global cultural icon of France and one of the most recognisable structures in the world.

Le 58 Tour Eiffel - Located on the first level of the Eiffel Tower, Le 58 Tour Eiffel offers visitors a unique dining experience with spectacular views of Paris. The restaurant serves French cuisine in a casual setting, making it a perfect spot for lunch or dinner while exploring the tower.

Le Jules Verne - Le Jules Verne is a gourmet restaurant located on the second floor of the Eiffel Tower. Managed by three-star chef Frédéric Anton, the restaurant offers an exquisite dining experience with a Michelin star rating. Guests can enjoy sophisticated French cuisine while taking in breathtaking views of the city.

Champ de Mars - The Champ de Mars is a large public greenspace in Paris, located at the foot of the Eiffel Tower. It is a popular spot for picnics, leisurely walks, and enjoying the outdoors. The park offers a fantastic vantage point for admiring the Eiffel Tower, especially at night when the tower is beautifully illuminated.

Notre-Dame de Paris - Notre-Dame de Paris is a medieval Catholic cathedral on the Île de la Cité in Paris, France. It is considered one of the finest examples of French Gothic architecture, featuring pioneering use of the rib vault and flying buttress, colorful rose windows, and an abundance of sculptural decoration. The cathedral has three pipe organs and immense church bells. It has been a key site for many historical events, including the coronation of Napoleon and the celebration of the Liberation of Paris. Despite suffering damage from a fire in 2019, restoration efforts are underway to reopen the cathedral by December 2024.

Sacré-Cœur Basilica - The Basilica of Sacré Coeur de Montmartre, commonly known as Sacré-Cœur Basilica, is a Roman Catholic church and minor basilica in Paris dedicated to the Sacred Heart of Jesus. It is located at the summit of the butte of Montmartre, offering a panoramic view of the city from its dome. The basilica is a national historic monument, known for its Romano-Byzantine architecture, and houses the largest mosaic in the world, The Triumph of the Sacred Heart of Jesus. Visitors can explore the interior's chapels, crypt, and the grand organ, or enjoy the garden for meditation. The top of the dome is accessible to tourists, providing a spectacular view of Paris.

Panthéon - The Panthéon in Paris is a monumental example of Neoclassicism, featuring a striking dome influenced by Bramante's Tempietto. Originally intended as a church dedicated to Saint Genevieve, it was transformed into a mausoleum during the French Revolution, housing the remains of distinguished French citizens. Visitors can explore the architecture, the Foucault pendulum demonstrating the Earth's rotation, and the crypt where notable figures such as Voltaire, Rousseau, and Marie Curie are interred. The building's history reflects the changing political and social landscape of France, from its inception under King Louis XV to its role in the French Revolution and beyond.

Arc de Triomphe - The Arc de Triomphe de l'Étoile is a monumental triumphal arch in Paris, France, honoring those who fought for France in the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars. Visitors can explore the rich history of the monument, view the names of French victories and generals inscribed on its surfaces, and pay respects at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier from World War I. The arch offers a panoramic view of Paris from its terrace, accessible via a lift and a final climb of 40 steps. The monument also houses a small museum detailing its construction and significance.

Forbidden City - The Forbidden City, located in the heart of Beijing, China, is a massive palace complex that served as the home of emperors and their households for almost 500 years. It is now a museum and one of China's most significant historical sites, showcasing ancient Chinese architecture and cultural heritage.

The Forbidden Corner - Located in the Yorkshire Dales, England, The Forbidden Corner is a unique and whimsical garden filled with a labyrinth of tunnels, chambers, and surprises around every corner. It's a place of exploration and adventure, appealing to both children and adults.

Forbidden Planet - Forbidden Planet is a chain of comic book and pop culture merchandise stores. It offers a wide range of products, including comics, graphic novels, toys, and collectibles, catering to fans of science fiction, fantasy, and superhero genres.

Forbidden Fruit Winery - Situated in the Similkameen Valley of British Columbia, Canada, Forbidden Fruit Winery is known for its award-winning organic fruit wines. The winery offers tastings and tours, providing visitors with an insight into the winemaking process and the opportunity to sample unique wines made from cherries, peaches, and other fruits.

Steak frites - For the quintessential bistrot dish, steak frites, head to one of Paris’ atmospheric French brasseries, complete with brass fittings, linen tablecloths (red gingham optional) and smart, aproned waiting staff. These restaurants are so integral to the city’s dining scene, even multi-Michelin-starred chef Alain Ducasse has opened one: Champeaux in Les Halles.

Bar Hemingway - The city’s most famous bar is tucked away inside The Ritz and celebrates the life and work of its most famous barfly, Ernest Hemingway. Try a sublime cocktail mixed by legendary British barman Colin Field, who has run the bar since 1994.

Pierre Hermé - Until supreme patissier Pierre Hermé reinvented these small, smooth meringues filled with ganache, macarons were a fairly unassuming item in the extensive range of French patisserie. This delicate pastry has taken the world by storm but its birthplace is resolutely Paris.

Balagan - One of the hottest tables in town is at Balagan where chefs Assaf Granit and Dan Yosha and their team are serving fresh, vibrant vegetable, fish and meat dishes lifted with perfectly pitched spices, tahini and citrus.

Bofinger - This brasserie staple originally hails from Alsace, the border region in eastern France, but it came to the French capital at the end of the 19th century when the region was annexed by Germany and refugees fled to Paris. Choucroute is the French word for sauerkraut, a huge serving of white cabbage cooked in riesling, duck or pork fat, with herbs and garlic and topped with sausages and pork knuckle.

Le Meurice - Is it really an orange? As you slice into its shell, you soon realise patissier Cédric Grolet’s extraordinary desserts are something very special – this is actually mousse filled with mandarin and timut pepper compote. At just 32 years old, Grolet has established a worldwide following (mostly thanks to his Instagram account) for his fruit desserts, which look every bit like the real thing.

Jacques Genin - While the internationally-famous Ladurée and Pierre Hermé carve out their global operations, the chocolatier of choice for discerning Parisians is Jacques Genin. Head up to his elegant boutique and salon de thé (133 Rue de Turenne) not far from Place de la République to indulge in his exquisite and unusual flavours such as caper and basil, to sublime effect.
Angelina - One of the most elegant and popular salons de thé is Angelina on the Rue de Rivoli, where tea and coffee should come with their signature patisserie, Le Mont Blanc.
